 and traffickers as well as from experts, counselors, law enforcement officers, rescue and support groups, and others-this book is also a call to action, telling what we, as private citizens, can do to finally bring an end to this horrific crime.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHuman traffickingzUnited States. 0aSlaveryzUnited States. 4aactivist. 4acall to action. 4acommunity awareness. 4acommunity leader. 4ahuman rights violations. 4amodern day slave owners. 4amodern slavery. 4apedophilia. 4apolitical activism. 4apolitician. 4arescue. 4asexual abuse. 4aslaveholder. 4asold into slavery. 4asupport groups. 4asurvivor stories. 4atrauma. 4aunexpected slave owners. 4aunited states modern slaves. 4awhite slavery. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aSoodalter, Ron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520948037423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520948037.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles